Chapter 3

(P1)

Since the t-value from the regression of salary on years of experience is -2.2277729 with degrees of freedom 148 and alpha = 0.05, and this value is between critical values 1.980 at p=0.025 and 2.358 at p=0.01 from t-table with df=120, we can conclude that the p-value corresponding to our regression model is 0.01 < p < 0.025. Thus p < alpha. We reject the Null Hypothesis (H0:B1=0) at a significance level alpha = 0.05. A p-value < 0.05 means that if we assume the Null Hypothesis the probability we are correct is less than 0.05. Thus, if we assume B1=0 we have less than 0.05 probability of being correct. This result indicates there is a linear relationship between salary and years of experience guided by B1(slope).

(P2)

Since the t-value from the regression of salary on employee rating is 1.4684015 with degrees of freedom 148 and alpha = 0.05, and this value is between critical values 1.289 at p=0.10 and 1.658 at p=0.05 from t-table with df=120, we can conclude that the p-value corresponding to our regression model is p > 0.05. Thus p > alpha. We fail to reject the Null Hypothesis (H0:B1=0) at a significance level alpha = 0.05. A p-value = 0.05 means that if we assume the Null Hypothesis the probability we are correct is 0.05. Thus, if we assume B1=0 we have 0.05 probability of being correct.

###(P1)
#Salary on years of experience t-test, p-value at alpha = 0.05
n = length(manager$salary)

estimate_B <- function(X, Y){
  Xbar <- mean(X)
  Ybar <- mean(Y)
  b1hat <- sum((X - Xbar) * (Y - Ybar)) / sum ((X - Xbar)^2)
  b0hat <- Ybar - b1hat * Xbar
  return(c(b0hat, b1hat))
}

result = estimate_B(manager$yearsexp, manager$salary)
beta1_hat = result[2]
beta0_hat = result[1]
 
MSE = sum((manager$salary - (beta0_hat - beta1_hat * manager$yearsexp))^2) / (n - 2) 
se_beta1_hat = sqrt(MSE / sum((manager$yearsexp - mean(manager$yearsexp))^2))

t_value <- (beta1_hat - 0) / se_beta1_hat

# t(alpha=0.025, n - 2)

###(P3)
# Mean confidence interval 
RDG = function(b0, b1, X, sigma){
  n = length(X)
  Y = b0 + b1 * X + rnorm(n, sd = sigma)
  return(Y)
}

M = 10000
x_h = 3.5

X = runif(n,0,10)
sigma = 0.5
alpha = 0.05
total = 0

for (i in 1:M){
  ## generate a random sample
  Y = RDG(intercept2, slope2, X, sigma)
  
  ## get beta1_hat & beta0_hat
  result1 = estimate_B(X, Y)
  beta1_hatt = result1[2]
  beta0_hatt = result1[1]
  
  ## s.e.(beta0_hat + beta1_hat*x_h)
  MSE1 = sum((Y - (beta0_hatt - beta1_hatt * X))^2) / (n - 2)
  se1 = sqrt(MSE1 * (1/n + (mean(X) - x_h)^2 / sum((X - mean(X))^2)))
  
  ## C.I.
  lower3.5 = beta0_hatt + beta1_hatt * x_h - se1*qt(1-alpha/2, n - 2)
  upper3.5 = beta0_hatt + beta1_hatt * x_h + se1*qt(1-alpha/2, n - 2)
  
  ## whether the true parameter (beta0 + beta1*x_h) is within the C.I.
  total = total + 1*((intercept2 + slope2 * x_h >= lower3.5) & (intercept2 + slope2 * x_h <= upper3.5))
}


x2_h <- 8.5
total1 = 0

for (i in 1:M){
  ## generate a random sample
  Y1 = RDG(intercept2, slope2, X, sigma)
  
  ## get beta1_hat & beta0_hat
  resultt = estimate_B(X, Y1)
  beta1_hatt2 = resultt[2]
  beta0_hatt2 = resultt[1]
  
  ## s.e.(beta0_hat + beta1_hat*x_h)
  MSE12 = sum((Y - (beta0_hatt2 - beta1_hatt2 * X))^2) / (n - 2)
  se2 = sqrt(MSE12 * (1/n + (mean(X) - x2_h)^2 / sum((X - mean(X))^2)))
  
  ## C.I.
  lower8.5 = beta0_hatt2 + beta1_hatt2 * x2_h - se2*qt(1-alpha/2, n-2)
  upper8.5 = beta0_hatt2 + beta1_hatt2 * x2_h + se2*qt(1-alpha/2, n-2)
  
  ## whether the true parameter (beta0 + beta1*x_h) is within the C.I.
  total1 = total1 + 1*((intercept2 + slope2 * x2_h >= lower8.5) & (intercept2 + slope2 * x2_h <= upper8.5))
}

#regression model tips on bill and plot
library(readr)
restauranttips <- read_csv("restauranttips.csv")

plot(restauranttips$Bill, restauranttips$Tip, main = "Tips by amount of bill", ylab = "Tip", xlab = "Bill")

tip_bill_model <- lm(restauranttips$Tip ~ restauranttips$Bill)
abline(tip_bill_model, col = 'red')

summary(tip_bill_model)

#t-test to assess whether there is a linear relationship between the amount of the bill and the amount of the tip
N = length(restauranttips$Bill)

result8 = estimate_B(restauranttips$Bill, restauranttips$Tip)
beta1_hat8 = result8[2]
beta0_hat8 = result8[1]
 
MSE8 = sum((restauranttips$Tip - (beta0_hat8 - beta1_hat8 * restauranttips$Bill))^2) / (N - 2) 
se_beta1_hat8 = sqrt(MSE8 / sum((restauranttips$Bill - mean(restauranttips$Bill))^2))

t_value8 <- (beta1_hat8 - 0) / se_beta1_hat8

# t(0.05, N - 2) 
result6 = estimate_B(restauranttips$Bill, restauranttips$Tip)
beta1_hat6 = result6[2]
beta0_hat6 = result6[1]

intercept6 <- coef(lm(tip_bill_model))["(Intercept)"]
slope6 <- coef(lm(tip_bill_model))["restauranttips$Bill"]



#CI for slope
total6 = 0
X6 = runif(n,0,15)

for (i in 1:M){
  ## generate a random sample
  Y6 = RDG(intercept6, slope6, X6, sigma)
  
  ## get beta1_hat & beta0_hat
  result6 = estimate_B(X6, Y6)
  beta1_hat6 = result6[2]
  beta0_hat6 = result6[1]
  
  ## s.e.(beta1_hat)
  MSE6 = sum((Y6 - beta0_hat6 - beta1_hat6 * X6)^2) / (N - 2)
  se_beta1_hat6 = sqrt(MSE6 / sum((X6 - mean(X6))^2))
  
  ## C.I. for beta1
  lowerb = beta1_hat6 - se_beta1_hat6 * qt(1-alpha/2, N - 2)
  upperb = beta1_hat6 + se_beta1_hat6 * qt(1-alpha/2, N - 2)
  
  ## whether the true parameter beta1 is within the C.I.
  total6 = total6 + 1*((slope6 >= lowerb) & (slope6 <= upperb))
}
